Winter weather travel advisory in effect.

Brief burst of heavy snow and strong winds tonight.

Hazards:
Brief strong westerly winds gusting up to 85 km/h.
Brief bursts of heavy snow resulting in a quick 2 cm of accumulation.
Significantly reduced visibility in heavy snow and blowing snow.

Timing:
Tonight.

Discussion:
A sharp line of heavy flurries will move across the area tonight resulting in brief bursts of heavy snow. The heavy snow will combine with very strong winds to result in significantly reduced visibility at times. Motorists are advised to exercise caution.

Prepare for quickly changing and deteriorating travel conditions. Be prepared to adjust your driving with changing road conditions. Take extra care when walking or driving in affected areas.

For road conditions and other traveller information from the Ministry of Transportation, visit https://www.ontario.ca/511, https://www.twitter.com/511Ontario, or call 5-1-1.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Dense fog with near zero visibility continues in some localities.

Fog is likely to persist into the overnight hours and may become more extensive.

Conditions will improve on Thursday morning.

Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations.

If visibility is reduced while driving, slow down, watch for tail lights ahead and be prepared to stop.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring.

Maximum wind gusts: southeasterly 90 km/h.

Time span: Thursday afternoon and evening.

Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage.

Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

Snow squalls ending later this evening.

Hazards:
Locally heavy snowfall with additional accumulations up to 10 cm.
Peak snowfall rates of 2 to 5 cm per hour.
Poor visibility at times in heavy snow and blowing snow.

Timing:
Ending later this evening.

Discussion:
Lake effect snow squalls continue near Lake Superior, but will slowly shift southward out of the region as the evening progresses.

Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Road closures are possible.

Consider postponing non-essential travel until conditions improve. If you must travel, keep others informed of your schedule and destination and carry an emergency kit and mobile phone. Public Safety Canada encourages everyone to make an emergency plan and get an emergency kit with drinking water, food, medicine, a first-aid kit and a flashlight. For information on emergency plans and kits go to https://www.getprepared.gc.ca/.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Lake effect snow squalls continue.

Hazards:

Peak snowfall rates of 3 to 6 cm per hour.
Very poor to zero visibility at times in heavy snow and blowing snow.

Timing:
Tonight into Thursday morning. 

Discussion:
Lake effect snow squalls off Lake Huron will continue tonight as a low pressure system moves across the area, enhancing snowfall amounts. Snow squalls will then move south of the area Thursday morning.

Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Road closures are possible.

Consider postponing non-essential travel until conditions improve. If you must travel, keep others informed of your schedule and destination and carry an emergency kit and mobile phone. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Timing:

Discussion:

Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Road closures are possible.

Higher than normal water levels with large waves are expected near the coast on Thursday afternoon.

The combination
- of strong winds from the east
- of a moderate to significant surge set-up
- and a medium tidal range
could produce breaking sea conditions along the coast of the tip of the Gaspé Peninsula Thursday afternoon.

Buildings located in areas vulnerable to storm surge may be flooded.

Flooding is possible along the coastline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. The combination of surge and waves may cause impacts well inland.

This warning is in effect for parts of the coast due to the following hazard(s): Moderate storm surge. Higher than normal water levels.

Locations: western Bay of Chaleur.

Maximum wave heights: 2 to 3 metres, breaking upon approach to shore.

Time span: thursday afternoon and evening near high tide.

High tide: 5 P.M. to 7 P.M. Thursday.

Remarks: Large waves and pounding surf will produce higher than normal water levels along the coast, especially near high tide.

Flooding is possible along the coastline. The combination of surge and waves may cause damage along the coast.

Locations: Red Bay to L'Anse au Clair. 

Total snowfall: 15 to 25 cm. Highest amounts are expected inland and over higher terrain. 

Maximum wind gusts: southeasterly 80 km/h.

Time span: Thursday night until Friday morning.

Similar storms in the past have caused:
- hazardous driving conditions
- scattered utility outages
- delays or cancellations of ferry services

Remarks: Snow, at times heavy, will begin overnight on Thursday. Snow will transition to, or mix with, rain on Friday morning as temperatures begin to rise above zero.

Gusty winds will lead to locally reduced visibility over higher terrain and along the Trans-Labrador Highway in blowing snow.

Be prepared to adjust your driving with changing road conditions. If visibility is reduced while driving, slow down, watch for tail lights ahead and be prepared to stop.

Poor driving conditions with the first significant snowfall event.

What:
Additional snowfall amounts near 10 centimetres are expected. Moderate snowfall at times causing reduced visibility.

When:
Until Thursday morning.

Where:
The Outaouais, Laurentians and Northern Lanaudière areas. Snowfall amounts will be more significant over higher terrain.

Additional information:
A low pressure system from the Canadian Prairies will move across the Great Lakes and bring snow to Quebec. The evening commute may be impacted today, especially in the Outaouais and Laurentians areas.

Poor weather conditions may contribute to transportation delays. There may be a significant impact on rush hour traffic in urban areas.

Be prepared to adjust your driving with changing road conditions.

Strong winds with severe and damaging gusts are expected or occurring.

Maximum gusts: 80 to 100 km/h, except 140 to 150 in areas prone to enhanced southeasterlies.

Locations: Bay St. George to Port Saunders and the Straits.

Time span: Thursday evening until overnight Thursday night or early Friday morning.

Similar storms in the past have resulted in:
- hazardous driving conditions and toppling of high sided vehicles

Snow squalls continuing tonight. 

Hazards:
Additional snowfall accumulations of 10 to 20 cm.
Peak snowfall rates of 2 to 5 cm per hour.
Very poor visibility at times in heavy snow and blowing snow.
Isolated power outages possible due to the heavy wet nature of the snow.

Timing:
Tonight.

Discussion:
Lake effect snow squalls off Georgian Bay will continue. Snowfall amounts will be enhanced at times as a low pressure system will move through the area. Snow will taper off by Thursday morning.

Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Road closures are possible.

Consider postponing non-essential travel until conditions improve. If you must travel, keep others informed of your schedule and destination and carry an emergency kit and mobile phone. Public Safety Canada encourages everyone to make an emergency plan and get an emergency kit with drinking water, food, medicine, a first-aid kit and a flashlight. For information on emergency plans and kits go to https://www.getprepared.gc.ca/.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring.

Where: 
- Metro Vancouver, Southern Gulf Islands, East Vancouver Island, Sunshine Coast.
